"Yes, captain. They must be on their way now, we've given them time to get rations from the mess hall." At 5:00 sharp, Company Exodus was assembled at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a crate and began to speak.
"We're deploying to FOB I-131, 80 kilometers from Ianlos. We need to support the ongoing siege and the planned attack on Ianlos to put down the insurgency. From there, we'll have an advanced position and a base at the foot of the mountains," explained Shaw. "Gather your units, and board."
The company dispersed, each one joining their unit, and the sergeants had them climb onto the tanks. Cohren climbed aboard one of the armored vehicles, at the front of the convoy, and joined Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered their arrival a few days earlier, but he didn't know much about them. Sitting on the side, legs dangling, he adjusted his backpack and his radio equipment, which was connected to his earpiece and his throat microphone.
"Hey Cohren, is Harris still with Snowball?", asked Nemic as they settled in.
"You mean the chicken he stole?", Cohren remembered the morning when they stole it from a farm. "Yes, I'm sure".
Cohren cast a glance at one of the tanks and spotted Harris with his unit. From the back of his backpack, he could just make out the movement of a small chicken shaking its head to observe the surroundings.
"Yeah, he's still with Snowball," replied Cohren as the turret of the tank creaked open to let his commander pass through.
"All the tanks are on their way," declared calmly, but clearly the commander in his helmet. The engines of a platoon of tanks and Strykers roared as they began to advance. The Kronos on which Cohren was seated jerked as its brakes were released and it started moving to fall into formation. The tanks deployed in a V to cross the plains of Itania. The winter storms had frozen the marshes and forests, but the mud was still there.
About an hour later, one of the new recruits, named Orson in Cohren's memory, spoke up. "Lieutenant, you're here since the beginning of the war, aren't you?"
"Yeah, Operation Storm of Fire," replied Cohren. "We thought we'd wrap it up in a few weeks, but... we underestimated them."
"Underestimate is a weak word," said Nemic as he joined in the conversation. "They had more arms and men than we anticipated. They managed to knock out the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks, and Erebus last month. Dammit, we should see it from the road where we are."
"Well, I'll hold up for the Federation," said Orson a bit provocatively. "I won't let these terrorists scare me."
"You say that now, but by experience, I know that new young recruits of 18 years old like you take cover as soon as you hear a shot," declared Craith.
"I think we'll soon find out," said Cohren laughing. Orson did not follow up on the conversation.
"Exodus XO, Exodus CO," crackled Cohren's radio. "We're detecting thermal signatures approximately 300 meters, 20 degrees right."
Cohren climbed up to the top of the tank and put on his optical glasses. By activating the thermal vision, he could see distant thermal signatures.
"Yes, I see them," Cohren replied via his throat microphone.
"Enemies?", asked the other recruit, Natayla.
"Impossible to tell," declared Cohren. He activated his microphone and said: "Company Exodus, do not fire unless fired upon, let them leave."
As they drew closer, the small thermal signatures passed from blurry spots to more distinct shapes. As they drew closer still, one of them ran towards something, seized it, then rushed back to the small ridge where they were. The silhouettes took up firing positions.
"We have contacts", Shaw shouted into the radio, as orange tracers were fired from the ridge. The bullets ricocheted off the sides of the tanks, while the soldiers jumped off the vehicles to take cover behind them. A tank-busting missile whizzed by and exploded on the ground behind the formation, sending debris flying onto one of the vehicles. Another missile hit the side of a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. Its crew extricated themselves and dove to take cover as the ammunition ignited.
"Iron 1-2 and &-, 25 degrees right, 275 meters. 'Fire'", the tank platoon commander shouted into the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, their shells flying towards the ridge and exploding, sending mud and rocks into the air.
"Send the Senti", Knoxx cried, watching the ridge through his binoculars. The rear of one of the Cerberus opened and an unarmed soldier wearing a special helmet emerged. He yelled orders into a square microphone and two Senti, or Sentinelles in their official name, rushed outside. Their thin metal arms and legs swung forward as they sprinted. They were armed, but their arms were strapped to their backs.
"Do we kill them or capture them?", Craith asked as they watched.
"It seems we capture them", Cohren advanced as the two Senti disappeared into a cloud of ashes and smoke. Cries and gunfire echoed from the ridge, but quickly ceased. A moment later, the two Senti returned, dragging someone behind them, whose boots trailed on the ground. Once in safety near the platoon, they threw the individual to the ground. He groaned in pain as he fell into the mud and snow.
Shaw marched toward the individual, who was starting to get up. He turned to one of the Sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, chief", replied the Sentinel. "The others ran on foot."
Shaw nodded his head and turned to Cohren and Craith, who were standing next to him. "Would both of you have the kindness to get rid of this man?"
